  "text": "With the continued improvement of OCT system speeds due to hardware advances, methods for OCTA shifted from comparing between adjacent A-scans to between sequential cross-sectional B-scans. The increased time separation ensured that slower flow in the microvasculature would be detected. In 2009, Fingler et al. [CITATION_1] used a 25-kHz SD-OCT system and a phase variance approach over 10 repeat B-scans at the same location to show microvasculature that was analogous to FA in human eyes. In 2011, Kim et al. [CITATION_2] used a 125-kHz SD-OCT system to image with a larger field of view. They used montaging/ stitching of 10 volumes to generate an OCT angiogram with coverage comparable to FA.",
